            <ce:data-availability id="da0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st0030">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Data is available at the following DOI: <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://doi.org/10.5061/dryad.xd2547drc" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/research-data" id="ir1005" xlink:type="simple">10.5061/dryad.xd2547drc</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0035">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">The global carbon (C) budget remains incomplete, as it primarily accounts for terrestrial and marine stocks but lacks specificity in aquatic ecosystems and transitional ecotones (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0115" refid="bb0160">Friedlingstein et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0120" refid="bb0340">Matthews et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0125" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). C stock estimates often concentrate on the aboveground biomass found in tropical (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0130" refid="bb0160">Friedlingstein et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) and temperate forests (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0135" refid="bb0005">Acharya et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0140" refid="bb0155">Frank et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0145" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Incomplete global C stock estimates for regions outside of these ecosystems limits our understanding of uncertainty in C accounting and thus our ability to address gaps within the global terrestrial carbon budget (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0150" refid="bb0160">Friedlingstein et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). To date, C flux characterization in rivers and riparian ecosystems are not systematically considered within global C budget calculations (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0155" refid="bb0160">Friedlingstein et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Available estimates suggest these uncertainties in terrestrial C accounting may be primarily due to the 20–50% of the 5.6 Pg C yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> entering freshwater systems from terrestrial sources that remain unaccounted for in shallow sea C deposits (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0160" refid="bb0025">Aufdenkampe et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0165" refid="bb0045">Battin et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0170" refid="bb0100">Cole et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0175" refid="bb0645">Wohl, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). While only accounting for 2% of land surfaces globally, floodplains are thought to store up to 8% of total soil organic C (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0180" refid="bb0215">Hiederer and Köchy, 2011</ce:cross-ref>) by trapping 90% or more of riverine sediment yield (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0185" refid="bb0610">Valett et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>). Additionally, <ce:cross-ref id="cf0190" refid="bb0650">Wohl et al. (2012)</ce:cross-ref> documented that laterally unconfined valley bottom areas of river corridors (&lt;25% of the system) stored more that 75% of the C within the river system and <ce:cross-ref id="cf0195" refid="bb0310">Lininger et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> estimated that some floodplain areas may hold 68% more than the highest soil organic C values currently published within the literature. Although C residence time can be reduced by altered hydrology or land use (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0200" refid="bb0655">Wohl et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), <ce:cross-ref id="cf0205" refid="bb0225">Hoffmann (2022)</ce:cross-ref> still found up to 10% of the missing terrestrial C is likely held within floodplains. The coarseness but large magnitude of these prior findings, and remaining uncertainties in floodplain C fluxes, suggest that improved C stock quantification within floodplain riparian zones is essential.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">At the riverine aquatic and terrestrial transition zone, riparian corridors along geomorphic floodplains are characterized by flood disturbance events at seasonal, annual, or decadal intervals (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0210" refid="bb0190">Gregory et al., 1991</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0215" refid="bb0410">Naiman and Décamps, 1997</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0220" refid="bb0595">Tockner and Stanford, 2002</ce:cross-ref>). As a result of being fluvially dynamic transition zones, these riparian floodplains support a mosaic of habitats and diverse ecosystem services (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0225" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0230" refid="bb0365">McClain et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0235" refid="bb0545">Stella et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), such as nutrient cycling and carbon storage (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0240" refid="bb0225">Hoffmann, 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0245" refid="bb0475">Reed et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0250" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). The extent of floodplain and riparian zones and the ecosystem services they provide is proportionate to the size of the adjacent river (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0255" refid="bb0295">Larsen et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>). This is concerning because of the extensive anthropogenic alterations on most of world's largest rivers including 70% of the Mississippi River Valley (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0260" refid="bb0440">Opperman et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>), up to 99% of California's Central Valley riparian zones (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0265" refid="bb0250">Katibah, 1984</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0270" refid="bb0445">Opperman et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0275" refid="bb0480">Reiner and Griggs, 1989</ce:cross-ref>), and France's upper Rhône River which has been identified as a completely altered river corridor (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0280" refid="bb0415">Naiman et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cf0285" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> identified the three largest and most persistent C reservoirs in riparian floodplains capable of long-term carbon sequestration (100 &lt; years): <ce:bold>(1) standing biomass</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>(2) large wood</ce:bold> (LWD), and <ce:bold>(3) floodplain surfaces</ce:bold> (litter, organic matter, and topsoil). Carbon stock quantification efforts within floodplain and riparian corridors, though primarily limited to temperate and tropical regions (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0290" refid="bb0220">Hinshaw and Wohl, 2021</ce:cross-ref>), postulate that riparian floodplains are highly effective at C cycling (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0295" refid="bb0310">Lininger et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). The cyclical pattern of flooding and drying leads to the development of organically rich soils that capture considerable quantities of C, wherein Mediterranean floodplain soils have measured up to 286 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> of organic C (<ce:cross-ref id="cf7300" refid="bb1005">D’Elia et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0300" refid="bb0540">Steger et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:cross-ref id="cf0305" refid="t0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="t0005"/> summarizes available quantified C stock values within standing biomass, LWD, and floodplain surfaces in Mediterranean regions. When considered with temperate floodplain C stocks values, which hold up to 2794 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, global floodplain C storage accounts for an estimated 125 Pg (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0310" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>), which, for context, exceeds the 115 Pg C currently held within total global natural gas reserves (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0315" refid="bb0160">Friedlingstein et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Riparian floodplains have become a top priority for ecological restoration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0320" refid="bb0550">Strassburg et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>) because of the disproportionately high quantity of ecosystem services provided within (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0325" refid="bb0135">Dybala et al., 2019b</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0330" refid="bb0485">Riis et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), and their potential value to mitigate climate change (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0335" refid="bb0065">Capon et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). Despite this recognition and resources available supporting implementation (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0340" refid="bb0230">Holl, 2020</ce:cross-ref>), widespread restoration actions explicitly targeting C sequestration in riparian floodplains remains limited (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0345" refid="bb0200">Gutierrez et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0350" refid="bb0450">Palmer et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). However, implementing concepts that foster Nature-based Solutions (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0355" refid="bb0505">Seddon et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0360" refid="bb0620">Walters, 2016</ce:cross-ref>), multi-benefit restoration approaches (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0365" refid="bb0515">Serra-Llobet et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), or government initiatives like California's Multi-benefit Land Repurposing Program (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0370" refid="bb0120">DOC, 2022</ce:cross-ref>) can expand the number of projects that increase riparian floodplain C stocks while targeting biodiversity, flood mitigation, and other objectives (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0375" refid="bb0075">Castro et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0380" refid="bb0230">Holl, 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0385" refid="bb0325">Mansourian et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">To support efforts that focus on multiple benefits while still accumulating C, we quantify C across the three largest stocks in riparian areas (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0390" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) through a multidecadal chronosequence of restoration actions along five kilometers of a Mediterranean river. In doing so, this study aims to better identify and quantify C stocks in floodplain and riparian ecosystems and assess the influence of restoration treatments on C stocks when C stock accumulation was not the specified objective within a Mediterranean climate.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">We ask the following questions:<ce:list id="l0010">
                        <ce:list-item id="li0035">
                           <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">How much C exists within C stocks in restored Mediterranean-montane riparian floodplains? By quantifying the three main C stocks (standing biomass, large wood, and floodplain surfaces) following restoration, we explore potential carbon sequestration in these ecosystems.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="li0040">
                           <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">Do C stocks vary across restoration treatment types and/or time? Understanding how initial conditions and the treatments applied influence C storage can help inform more effective restoration strategies.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="li0045">
                           <ce:label>(3)</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Do specific restoration approaches facilitate a desired trajectory toward remnant floodplain forest over shorter time domains? Restoration strategies can vary widely, from the types of species planted or methods used to prepare the site for restoration, to the underlying biophysical processes. We explore how different approaches can impact the carbon sequestration potential of restored riparian ecosystems, with the goal of identifying the most effective strategies for maximizing C stocks.</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                     </ce:list>
                  </ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0040">Theory</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Although the theoretical basis of restoration ecology has existed since the 1980s, formal recognition is more recent (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0395" refid="bb0510">SER, 2004</ce:cross-ref>), and many river restoration activities predate this articulation, often lacking theoretical underpinnings (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0400" refid="bb0050">Bernhardt et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0405" refid="bb0275">Kondolf et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0410" refid="bb0280">Lake et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0415" refid="bb0290">Larkin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Because many of the initial restoration activities at CRP predate modern restoration ecology frameworks, these restorations treatments also lack formal hypotheses or experimental design. Trends observed within this work, instead, reflect space for time replacement (i.e., chronosequence) and before-after-control-impact evaluations without site specific ‘success’ or ‘failure’ results based on C values (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0420" refid="bb0420">Napora et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">In the absence of a theoretical underpinning for many of the restoration treatment actions evaluated herein, it is essential to establish a uniform theoretical framework to investigate the potentially competing outcomes of our investigation. A fundamental objective across floodplain restoration techniques is to restore a floodplain to some degree of functionality found within adjacent remnant riparian forests (e.g., climax-stage <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic>-dominant forest, maximum carbon stock accumulation, or a heterogenous forest structure). Concurrently, some practitioners expect specific restoration techniques to support their objective faster or better than other techniques (e.g., assisted restoration approaches accumulate C stock faster than process-based restoration approaches). Because we are evaluating multiple restoration actions at varying ages since treatment, we first quantify C stock values within standing biomass, large wood, and floodplain surfaces at the individual plot level. Then, to evaluate resulting C values via time, treatment, or other factor, we constructed competing hypotheses essential to contextualize resulting C trends and observations:</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0045">Non-linearity hypothesis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">The relationship between time since restoration and carbon storage may not be linear (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0425" refid="bb0115">Costanza et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). For many tree species, such as <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic>, found at this site, carbon uptake may increase rapidly during propagation and early growth stages but slow or even experience a momentary decline as competition forces increased individual mortality within a stand (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0430" refid="bb0210">Harper et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Similar examples may be possible within restoration treatments as vegetation establishes, but slows in C accumulation as the ecosystem matures and reaches pseudo-equilibrium rather than continued growth (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0435" refid="bb0470">Qiu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0050">Habitat heterogeneity hypothesis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Restoration actions are varied and dispersed across time and space. Restoration actions across broad areas with additionally varying environmental conditions could result in increased spatial heterogeneity (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0440" refid="bb0290">Larkin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0445" refid="bb0640">Wohl, 2016</ce:cross-ref>), especially in places where flood regimes and river flow reconnection allowed for increased geomorphic complexity (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0450" refid="bb0600">Tockner et al., 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0455" refid="bb0625">Ward et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). The varying restoration actions across a mosaic of conditions could result in differential C accumulation rates and thus diverse standing C stock values depending on specific characteristics of each site, such as soil type, hydrology, or pre-existing vegetation. Therefore, instead of observing a uniform pattern of increased C across sites, we would expect differential responses driven by local characteristics within treatments. Habitat heterogeneity as a means to create biodiversity, ecological functionality, or other ecosystem-based outcomes, however, remains contested (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0460" refid="bb0450">Palmer et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0055">Disturbance</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Disturbance regimes remain a primary driver of species diversity (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0465" refid="bb0625">Ward et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). In this study system, for example, there are many sources of disturbance, including displacement of top soil (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0470" refid="bb0305">Limpert et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), removal of riparian forests (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0475" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>), and hydrological disconnection (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0480" refid="bb0260">Knox et al., 2022a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0485" refid="bb0265">Knox et al., 2022b</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0490" refid="bb0440">Opperman et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Each varies in magnitude and extent but has the potential to reduce or remove C cycling mechanisms. Alternatively, restoring a natural disturbance regime, such as flooding or fire, can drive carbon sequestration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0495" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al., 2019a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0500" refid="bb0435">Opperman, 2012</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0505" refid="bb0555">Sutfin and Wohl, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). The initial disturbance caused by restoration activities, such as levee removal, could lead to a temporary decrease in C, however. The rate and degree to which C stocks recovers could then depend on factors such as the degree of degradation prior to restoration, extent of the initial disturbance, restoration treatment actions, and the resilience of the specific ecosystem.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0060">Species composition</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">Some restoration actions investigated here include propagating specific plant species, altering community composition, and perhaps C storage capacity. Different plant species have different growth rates, lifespans, and structures, influencing how much C they accumulate and how quickly, see ‘C%’ in <ce:bold>Appendix B</ce:bold>. Some restoration practitioners consider planting to be a means to ‘jump-start’ C accumulation within restored landscapes based on an expectation of increased growth (biomass accumulation) in the decade following restoration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0510" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al., 2019a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0515" refid="bb0135">Dybala et al., 2019b</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, active restoration efforts may prioritize single-species monocultures based on the potential of a single C-dense species being able to obtain more biomass than a diverse polyculture (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0520" refid="bb0070">Cardinale et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>), while other approaches may plant a limited number of mid- to late-seral stage woody species to provide enough species diversity to enhance C stock accumulation (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0525" refid="bb0085">Chen et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0530" refid="bb0660">Xu et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Evidence to support either planting scheme is limited with most research conducted finding little support in understory recruitment (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0535" refid="bb0615">Viers et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>), survival (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0540" refid="bb0010">Albrecht et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), or C sequestration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0545" refid="bb0350">Matzek et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0065">Materials and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0070">Study location and sampling strategy</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.1.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0075">Study site characteristics</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">In California's Central Valley, the Cosumnes River is the largest river on the western slope of the Sierra Nevada without a major dam project. As a tributary of the San Joaquin River via the Mokelumne River, the Cosumnes River drains 2460 km from its headwaters ∼2400 m above sea level to 0 m at its confluence. Once a mosaic of anastomosing floodplain and riparian landscapes (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0550" refid="bb0145">Florsheim and Mount, 2003</ce:cross-ref>), anthropogenic alterations have confined most of the Cosumnes River to a single channel (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0555" refid="bb0630">Whipple et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). In the lower reach, however, attempts to restore riparian forest habitats and floodplain connectivity has been ongoing for nearly four decades within the Cosumnes River Preserve (CRP) (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0560" refid="bb0580">Swenson et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0565" refid="bb0575">Swenson et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>). The CRP includes the 7 km river reach that is the focus of this study (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0570" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.1.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0080">Plot location selection</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">In years 2012–2013, 92 plots were surveyed for woody species composition and biomass measurements for all stems with a diameter at breast height (DBH) &gt;5 cm. These plots were identified using a stratified random approach - stratified to prioritize plot placement within all treatments available at the time. For some locations, this was the first observation documented since the treatment had been applied.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">In 2020–2021, we resurveyed 48 of the 92 plots and added an additional 28 plots located within areas that were not part of CRP in 2012–13. Four of the 28 plots had standing woody biomass and 24 plots did not. During the 2020–21 resurvey, several plots measured in 2012–13 no longer possessed any woody stems &gt;5 cm DBH (four plots) or were located in an area we were not able to access due to permit limitations (ten plots), thus could not be resurveyed. Of the remaining 78 plots, we prioritized selecting plots in as many treatments as possible, thus where a treatment included many plots (e.g. 16 plots within one treatment area), we randomly selected points to resurvey, ultimately resulting in 48 selected points to resurvey (the remaining 44 plots not selected are available in <ce:bold>Appendix A</ce:bold>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The resulting 76 plots surveyed in 2020–21 are shown in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0575" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref> with 52 (48 resurveyed and 4 plots added in 2020–21) biomass, litter, and soil plots as green triangles and 24 litter and soil plots (added in 2020–21) as gold circles. Three of the ‘litter and soil only’ plots are within active agriculture to represent what year-zero would be prior to any restoration treatment activities. The agricultural lands did not include a cover-crop or any nutrient additions documented prior to sampling. Biomass plots were 20 m × 20 m for both data collection periods. Within each plot, we assessed woody species composition, stem DBH, and stem height. We also evaluated C within litter, and quantified total C and nitrogen (N) within the top 5 cm of soil for all 2020–21 plots. With these variables, we quantify the three largest stores of C within riparian floodplain ecosystems (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0580" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>): standing biomass, large wood, and floodplain surfaces.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0055" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.1.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0085">Treatment type</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">We investigated C stocks across 23 treatments ranging from six to &gt;100 years since year zero, which is the year a treatment was applied or agriculture was no longer taking place. <ce:cross-ref id="cf0585" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="t0010"/> provides details for each treatment, number of samples within each treatment, and years of treatment actions. We categorized treatments into four action types, as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0590" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cf0595" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>. <ce:italic>Process</ce:italic>-based restoration actions are limited to floodplain reconnection, land abandonment, or removal of man-made structures allowing for natural processes that had been prevented by lack of channel flow access (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0600" refid="bb0090">Ciotti et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0605" refid="bb0150">Ford, 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0610" refid="bb0400">Mount et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:italic>Assisted</ce:italic> restoration actions include intensive planting schemes or integrated projects to fast-forward through riparian successional stages and facilitate specific outcomes, such as increase biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0615" refid="bb0235">Holl and Aide, 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0620" refid="bb0240">Holl and Brancalion, 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0625" refid="bb0380">Meli et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), or to achieve a specific aesthetic (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0630" refid="bb0465">Podolak and Kondolf, 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0635" refid="bb0635">Wilson et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Because many restoration sites are abandoned after initial treatment (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0640" refid="bb0055">Brancalion et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>), or other events may arise, such as localized flooding from an unplanned levee failure (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0645" refid="bb0585">The Nature Conservancy, 2022</ce:cross-ref>), a variety of combinations between process and assisted actions are identified here as <ce:italic>Hybrid</ce:italic>. Several of the largest remaining remnant riparian forests in the Central Valley are interspersed within CRP and considered here as the late-seral (“Tall Forest” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0650" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>) and climax (“Shaw Forest” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0655" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>) stages referred to as <ce:italic>Remnant</ce:italic> here after (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0660" refid="bb0605">Tu, 2000</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0665" refid="bb0630">Whipple et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">To statistically evaluate the influence of treatment and treatment type on C stock values, we conducted a one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0670" refid="bb0185">Gotelli and Ellison, 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0675" refid="bb0350">Matzek et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) evaluating the influence of treatment (“Treatment Action” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0680" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>), treatment type (“Treat Type” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0685" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>), and time (“Year Zero” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0690" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref> broken into decades) each as a single independent variable with the resulting C values for each stock and total C each as a dependent variable. We also conducted a two-way ANOVA (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0695" refid="bb0165">Fu et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>) to evaluate the influence of treatment versus treatment type when they are each combined with time against the same set of dependent variables as the one-way ANOVA.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0090">Standing biomass – Riparian Forest</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0065" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.2.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0095">Species specific characteristics</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">For the Mediterranean-montane riparian floodplains in California, woody species composition typically follows an established succession. Pioneer species are typically Fremont cottonwood (<ce:italic>Populus fremontii</ce:italic>) and/or willow species (e.g., <ce:italic>Salix gooddingii</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Salix laevigata</ce:italic> or <ce:italic>Salix exigua</ce:italic>) that often require bare substrate to propagate. Pioneer species such as <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> typically propagate in thick groves and grow rapidly creating high competition, ultimately resulting in extensive die-off with few survivors. The few survivors will grow into individual trees that dominate the upper canopy. This process of mass propagation and then extensive die-off also creates nutrient rich litter over the nutrient-poor, bare, sandy substrate, essential for early seral stage species to establish. These early seral species include <ce:italic>Acer negundo</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Fraxinus latifolia</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>S. lucida</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>S. gooddingii</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>S. laevigata</ce:italic>, or <ce:italic>S. exigua</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>Sambucus nigra</ce:italic> ssp. <ce:italic>caerulea</ce:italic> may establish as a transition species after the early species have established but before the mid-seral species establish. The mid to late seral stage community that eventually takes shape typically include single large individuals of <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> and a dense understory of <ce:italic>A. negundo</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic>, allowing shade-tolerant <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> saplings to propagate. Late seral Riparian Forests transition into a climax stage Oak Forest in tandem with <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> stems surpassing the standing canopy. As the understory can no longer be maintained and lower canopy individuals die off, the Oak forest transitions into a grassland. This transition results in the climax Oak savanna typical of floodplain terraces found in California's Central Valley (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0700" refid="bb0105">Conard et al., 1977</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0705" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0710" refid="bb0250">Katibah, 1984</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0070" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.2.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0100">Plot location selection</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">From the 92 plots surveyed within CRP in 2012–2013, we selected 48 plots to revisit and added 4 new plots during the 2020–2021 data collection (the resulting 52 plots are identified as ‘biomass’ plots within <ce:cross-ref id="cf0715" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). Within each plot, all stems with a DBH &gt;5 cm were measured and identified to the species level. Plot canopy height was measured with a rangefinder, drone-based LiDAR, or Structure from Motion altimetry (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0720" refid="bb0095">Clifton and Viers, 2024</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0075" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.2.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0105">Diameter to biomass</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">We calculated biomass for all stems using species-specific allometric equations (provided in <ce:bold>Appendix B</ce:bold>). Resulting biomass values for each stem were summed to the 400 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> extent of each plot (20 m × 20 m). Most stems fell within the normal range of biomass values for their species found in the literature, see average DBH and average height in <ce:bold>Appendix B -</ce:bold> with the exception of a limited number of large, individual <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> stems found within a limited number of Remnant plots. One plot was removed from statistical analysis because the total biomass, at 2037.6 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, was more than three times the interquartile range (249.5 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) above the third quantile (312.4 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) for biomass values in this study. This strong outlier was also characteristically dissimilar to all other plots being evaluated, though not unreasonable for the species within the context of California's Oak savanna. Historical accounts of <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> include measurements of 4.2 stems ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> of the 152 and 166 cm DBH found in this plot (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0725" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>). This plot is part of a series of Remnant type plots in the Oak savanna, the climax stage for this ecosystem, thus information regarding this restoration type is not lost. For these reasons, this plot is considered in characterizing remnant type woody plant community but excluded from numeric and statistical evaluations of biomass and C stock within.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0080" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.2.4</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0110">Calculating basal area</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">To calculate basal area, the original DBH (d) in cm was converted to the stem radius, then used in determining area. Using <ce:italic>Eq.</ce:italic> 
                           <ce:cross-ref id="cf0730" refid="fo0005">
                              <ce:italic>1</ce:italic>
                           </ce:cross-ref>, the basal area (BA) for each stem was summed to the plot level for a total BA value in cm<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, converted to m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, then extrapolated from the 400 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> plot to a 1 ha equivalent, with a final BA value in m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, the unit used in this study. This calculation is summarized in <ce:italic>Eq.</ce:italic> 
                           <ce:cross-ref id="cf0735" refid="fo0005">
                              <ce:italic>1</ce:italic>
                           </ce:cross-ref>.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="fo0005">
                                 <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">BA</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:munderover>
                                       <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:munderover>
                                    <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:msup>
                                       <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                          <mml:mfrac>
                                             <mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                          </mml:mfrac>
                                       </mml:mfenced>
                                       <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msup>
                                    <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                        </ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">While BA and biomass are each a way to measure productivity, comparing the two values can provide unique insight for differences in woody plant communities. <ce:cross-ref id="cf0740" refid="f0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/> provides BA compared to biomass for 2012–13 plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0745" refid="f0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>a) and 2020–21 plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0750" refid="f0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>b).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0085" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.2.5</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0115">Calculating biomass carbon</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">The C content of each stem was calculated using the species-specific carbon content value and the biomass value calculated for each stem via the species-specific allometric equation. Typically, a 50% C ratio is applied when calculating C from biomass determined using a general allometric equation (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0755" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al., 2019a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0760" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>), however, we utilized species specific C ratios and allometric equations, values and citations for each are provided in <ce:bold>Appendix B</ce:bold>.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">Biomass C content values per stem were summated to the plot level. The total C value in each plot was extrapolated from the 400 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> original plot area to Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> using <ce:italic>Eq.</ce:italic> 
                           <ce:cross-ref id="cf0765" refid="fo0010">
                              <ce:italic>2</ce:italic>
                           </ce:cross-ref>. In the equation, <ce:italic>k</ce:italic> is the plot total, in Megagrams per hectare, of each stem biomass in kilograms (<ce:italic>b</ce:italic>) multiplied by the species specific C content of each stem (<ce:italic>C</ce:italic>). For each species, the allometric equation, C content, and supporting information is provided in <ce:bold>Appendix B</ce:bold>. All biomass values were converted to kilograms prior to determining the C content or included within <ce:italic>Eq.</ce:italic> 
                           <ce:cross-ref id="cf0770" refid="fo0010">
                              <ce:italic>2</ce:italic>
                           </ce:cross-ref>.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="fo0010">
                                 <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si2.svg">
                                    <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>0.025</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:munderover>
                                       <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:munderover>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>b</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                        </ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0090" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0120">Large Wood</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">We collected LiDAR from a Phoenix Aerial AL 3 unpiloted aerial vehicle (UAV) in 2017, 2019, and 2020 for at least 100 ha in the northern restoration areas, the top section of <ce:cross-ref id="cf0775" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>. Concurrently, we deployed several other UAVs outfitted with multispectral imagers, consisting of true-color and near-infrared channels, to assist with vegetation mapping. The methods are further elaborated upon in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0780" refid="bb0095">Clifton and Viers (2024)</ce:cross-ref> and initial analyses are described in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0785" refid="bb0500">Seavy et al. (2009b)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">We created a volumetric model by differencing first and last returns from a LiDAR point cloud for large wood (LWD) deposited across the floodplain and channel surfaces (3D Analyst, ArcGIS Pro, ESRI Redlands, CA). LWD was discriminated from nearby vegetation using multiband image classification and heads up digitization.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">To calculate biomass, we applied <ce:italic>Eq.</ce:italic> 
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cf0790" refid="fo0015">
                           <ce:italic>3</ce:italic>
                        </ce:cross-ref> with specific gravity (g) of 0.6275 g cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup> for each year using the results from the given year's LWD volumetric model (v) (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0795" refid="bb0060">Campbell et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Upon physical examination of the LWD deposits, we estimated that 50% of LWD volumes consisted of biomass (w). We calculated C within LWD biomass by applying 49.4% (C). Both the specific gravity and carbon ratio are mean values for the species expected to most common within the LWD (primarily <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. fremontii)</ce:italic> because species characteristics are not available for each individual log or fragment (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0800" refid="bb0020">Asner and Mascaro, 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0805" refid="bb0110">Coomes et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0810" refid="bb0285">Lamlom and Savidge, 2003</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0815" refid="bb0390">Miles and Smith, 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0820" refid="bb0590">Thomas and Martin, 2012</ce:cross-ref>).<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fo0015">
                              <ce:label>(3)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si3.svg">
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">LWC</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">v</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>∗</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">w</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>∗</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">g</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>∗</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                     </ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0095" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0125">Floodplain surfaces</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0100" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.4.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0130">Litter and soil sample collection</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">A litter sample and a soil sample were each collected at all 52 biomass plots surveyed in 2020–21 and the additional 24 plot locations identified in 2020–21 without woody biomass, including the three agriculture reference plots, depicted as ‘soil core’ plots in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0825" refid="f0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>. At the center-point of each 400 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> plot, we placed a 412.9 cm<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> metal frame (8 in. x 8 in. square frame) and collected all ground material within the frame to the soil surface as litter. We used a clean knife to cut around the outside frame edge and delineate outside material from sample litter material, allowing for uniform litter sample collection (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0830" refid="f0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a<ce:float-anchor refid="f0015"/>). Once isolated from surrounding litter, the frame was lifted and all litter was collected into an air and water-tight container (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0835" refid="f0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>b), then retained for processing.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">Once the litter sample was collected, a 250 cm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> stainless steel soil core ring was inserted into the soil, following <ce:cross-ref id="cf0840" refid="bb0460">Petersen and Calvin (1986)</ce:cross-ref>, over the biomass and litter collection boundary center-point (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0845" refid="f0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>c). Soil sampling targeted topsoil because of the high concentration of C and N found within the uppermost soil layer in previous studies of floodplain soil C profiles in the area (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0850" refid="bb0540">Steger et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>) and to allow for more samples to be collected and processed.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0105" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.4.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0135">Litter sample processing</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Litter samples were weighed, oven dried at 105 °C until consistent weight (∼24 h), then mechanically ground to a uniform consistency. A litter subsample was heated to 550 °C for 2 h to determine organic matter content (OM) through the weight difference following loss on ignition (LOI) methods (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0855" refid="bb0385">Mercury Research Laboratory, 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Total C within litter was calculated by multiplying sample OM (net dry weight corrected via percent lost in the LOI) by 0.55, considered the carbon content of litter organic matter (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0860" refid="bb0125">Domke et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0865" refid="bb0525">Smith and Heath, 2002</ce:cross-ref>), and extrapolated to the full litter sample.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0110" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.4.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0140">Soil sample processing</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">For soil samples, we initially weighed, air-dried, and then oven dried each sample at 105 °C until consistent weight (∼24 h) (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0870" refid="bb0320">Magdoff, 1994</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0875" refid="bb0395">Molles et al., 1995</ce:cross-ref>). Initial weight and dry weight were used to determine bulk density, soil water content by volume, and mass (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0880" refid="bb0530">Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">Following <ce:cross-ref id="cf0885" refid="bb0430">Nimmo and Perkins (2002)</ce:cross-ref>, soil samples were passed through a 2 mm mesh, 4 mm mesh, and 8 mm mesh sieve to differentiate &lt;2 mm soil, 2–4 mm soil fraction, 4–8 mm soil fractions respectively. Any remaining material was considered &gt;8 mm soil fraction. While soil C analysis typically only considers that which is contained in the &lt;2 mm fraction (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0890" refid="bb0030">Baldock and Broos, 2012</ce:cross-ref>), we consider the C within each of the segregated fractions. Soil carbon (C) and nitrogen (N) were determined via Combustion Method performed by the UC Davis Analytical Laboratory (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0895" refid="bb0015">AOAC Official Method 972.43, 1997</ce:cross-ref>) for all fractions in all samples with more than ten grams of net sample fraction weight. Total C and Total N are compared for each aggregate size fraction and averaged values resulting in five Carbon-to-Nitrogen (C:N) ratios per plot.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">Total C within each soil sample were summed on a weighted basis, multiplying C content by relevant soil fraction and extrapolated to Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0115" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0145">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0120" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0150">Total carbon stocks</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">Across all plots, total C values range from 1.2 to 1099.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> averaging 129.1 ± 160.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> (mean ± standard deviation). Without the 1099.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> outlier, the total mean is 116.2 ± 115.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. As seen in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0900" refid="f0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0020"/>, the C values among plots in total and individual stocks are variable. To understand these individual stocks better, we explore them below. <ce:cross-ref id="cf0905" refid="t0015">
                           <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0015"/> provides a summary of C values contextualized by age, treatment type, and individual components.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">Process plots had an average total of 87.4 ± 89.3 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. The lowest values of the 33 process type plots are found in restoration sites that are less than a decade old, continue to have sand splay complexes actively forming, and lack established vegetation. When these 13 plots without established aboveground woody biomass are removed, the average total plot C value for process-based plots rises to 160.7 ± 65.6 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Unlike Process and Hybrid type plots that vary in age, Assisted plots were typically treated 30 to 35 years ago. Many younger plots were planned as Assisted but are now characterized as Hybrid because of levee failures or other plot-specific conditions. Agriculture reference plots averaged 22.3 ± 8.4 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. A detailed breakdown of C values by treatment is provided within <ce:cross-ref id="cf0910" refid="t0015">
                           <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">The one-way ANOVA conducted to evaluate the influence of treatment, type and time on resulting C values indicated that treatment type and time were each a significant influence (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value &lt;0.001). The treatment type one-way ANOVA indicated that Remnant plots were significantly different from all other treatment types (5 treatment combinations &lt;0.001). The one-way ANOVA evaluating time concluded that 6 comparisons were significantly different (&lt;0.001) including plots &gt;40 years since year zero compared to all other years and plots &lt;10 years since year zero compared to &lt;30 and &lt; 40 years plots.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">When we evaluated the influence of time combined with treatment type on plot C values using a two-way ANOVA, the combination accounted for more variance than either individual within a one-way ANOVA. Additionally, treatment type had a higher influence than time within the two-way ANOVA. The combination of treatment type and time accounted for 41% of variance according to the Tukey's HSD post-hoc test with seven treatment type combinations. The post-hoc test indicated substantial differences between treatment types and time combinations, four of which were significant between treatment types and two were significant between time combinations.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0125" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0155">Aboveground biomass carbon stocks</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">Within the aboveground biomass C stock, the average across all sites is 110.8 ± 103.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2020 and 96.2 ± 114.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2012–13. Remnant forests had the highest measurements averaging 216.5 ± 115.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2020 and 146.8 ± 88.4 in 2012–13. If the excluded Remnant plot, which accounted for 1010.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, were considered, the 2020 total average biomass value would be 128.0 ± 161.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">Remnant plots had diverse species compositions. <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> was the dominant species in 20% of plots while <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> was codominant in 33% of plots and <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>Prunus cerasifera</ce:italic> codominance occurred in 13% of plots. <ce:italic>A. negundo</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> codominance was present in 13% of plots. <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> dominance, <ce:italic>Juglans hindsii</ce:italic> dominance, and <ce:italic>A. negundo</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>J. hindsii</ce:italic> codominance each accounted for in 7% of plots. The remnant plots with the highest total C hold such large C stocks within individual, exceptionally large, Valley Oaks (<ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic>), characteristic of their status as climax stage species found in Oak savanna or Oak woodlands (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0915" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>) and as the largest Oak species in North America (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0920" refid="bb0375">McVay et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0925" refid="bb0535">Sork et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">Process type plots in 2020 had <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> dominance and <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>S. gooddingii</ce:italic> codominant plots encompassed 19% of plots each. <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> was represented in 14% of plots and <ce:italic>P. fremontii / S. laevigata</ce:italic> codominance occurred in 15% of plots. <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> was dominant in 10% and <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic> codominance occurred in 14% of plots. <ce:italic>S. lucida</ce:italic> dominant, <ce:italic>S. exigua</ce:italic> dominant, and <ce:italic>S. gooddingii</ce:italic> / <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> codominant plots each represented 5% of plots.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">Process plots had 96.3 ± 72.3 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> from biomass in 2020 and 123.4 ± 154.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2012–13. It must be noted that the four plots added in 2020–21, with values ranging from 0.6 to 2.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2020, were not measured in 2012–13 because they had not recruited or did not contain large enough saplings to be measured. If those four plots are considered as 0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> within the 2012–13 results, the average drops to 94.2 ± 146.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> for the 2012–13 Process plots.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">Assisted plots held 50.1 ± 33.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> within their biomass in 2020 compared to their 2012–13 value of 23.9 ± 29.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. These plots were dominated by <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> with 9% also having codominance of <ce:italic>F. latifolia</ce:italic> and 18% having codominance of <ce:italic>P. fremontii</ce:italic>. Within Hybrid type plots, biomass held 23.3 ± 22.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2020 down from 45.3 ± 57.1 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2012–13. These plots were dominated by <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> with 40% having co-dominance of <ce:italic>F. latifolia.</ce:italic>
                     </ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0130" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0160">Large Wood carbon stocks</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">Results for large wood (LWD) are only available for a single floodplain site, reconnected in 2014, and measured in 2017, 2019, and 2020. No records of LWD deposition elsewhere in CRP are available. Within this one restoration site, the area covered by LWD measured via site survey and delineation was 625, 2800, and 5400 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> in 2017, 2019, and 2020 respectively. Within these areal extents, LWD C mass ranged from 320 Mg C to 3500 Mg C (see <ce:cross-ref id="cf0930" refid="t0020">
                           <ce:bold>Table 4</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0020"/> for incremental values of volume and Mg C).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0135" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0165">Floodplain surface carbon stocks</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0140" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.4.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0170">Litter</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">From our survey, 72 of the 76 plots had litter at the time of soil sample collection. The four plots that lacked litter cover were found in Process type plots with the fewest years since treatment (&lt; 10 years). These plots were in areas with extant sand splays and lacked any standing biomass. Litter values, available by treatment type in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0935" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>, range from 0.2 to 48.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> with Remnant plots having the highest average values (6.4 ± 2.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>). Agricultural reference plots had an average of 1.2 ± 1.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0145" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.4.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0175">Soil</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">For each sample, the total soil Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> was determined by weighing C concentration in each aggregate size class (“Soil C" in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0940" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>) by the fraction it represented within the total soil sample (“netF” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0945" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>), resulting in a weighted total C in the top 5 cm soil (“Total Soil C ha<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>” in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0950" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>). Total soil C stock values ranged from 1.2 to 85.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Values within the &lt;2 mm fraction ranged from 1.0 to 31.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. These values are broken down by treatment type in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0955" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>. Agricultural total soil values averaged 21.1 ± 6.9 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Within soil samples, Remnant (60.4 ± 16.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and Assisted (52.3 ± 12.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) plots have the highest average C values across all soil fractions.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">The ability of soil C stocks to become long-term stores relies heavily on the C:N ratio and facilitated microbial digestion. To understand the relationship between soil C and the C:N ratio in these plots, we compared soil Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> against the C:N ratio for each fraction size (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0960" refid="f0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="f0025"/>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0290" view="all">Consistent with other soil studies (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0965" refid="bb0040">Batjes, 1996</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0970" refid="bb0315">Luo et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0975" refid="bb0530">Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), the C:N ratio and the &lt;2 mm soil fraction have a non-linear, log relationship, as seen in <ce:cross-ref id="cf0980" refid="f0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>. We evaluated the correlation between average C:N ratio and total soil C values as well as between &lt;2 mm C:N and &lt;2 mm soil C value by applying a Pearson coefficient. The correlation between total soil C value and average C:N was low (0.45) and did not improve substantially when total soil C was transformed via natural log (0.59). However, the correlation between the C value in the &lt;2 mm soil fraction and the C:N ratio within the &lt;2 mm soil fraction was much higher (0.66) with correlation highest between the natural log transformed C value in the &lt;2 mm soil fraction and the C:N ratio within the &lt;2 mm soil fraction (0.85) with the Pearson coefficient. Additionally, this relationship also aligns with the &lt;2 mm grain size being considered a more stable C stock that is either the result of microbial residues, for low C:N and high Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0985" refid="bb0205">Hao et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf0990" refid="bb0670">Zhou et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>), or in the organic form readily available for microbial digestion for high C:N (<ce:cross-ref id="cf0995" refid="bb0665">Zhou et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). While our investigation supports larger grain sizes being more volatile (see <ce:cross-ref id="cf1000" refid="f0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>), they do have the potential to contribute to longer-lived carbon stocks in the future.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0150" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.4.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0180">Soil carbon to nitrogen fraction</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">Soil C:N ratio values within &lt;2 mm grain size range from 3.5 to 17.5 across plots. The lowest single C:N ratio and lowest mean C:N ratio of 11.4 ± 3.2 was in Process type plots. Many of these Process type plots included active sand splay deposits. When Process type plots that were within a lobe of a sand-splay were not considered, the C:N ratio averaged 14.0 ± 1.7, aligning with Assisted type plots. Agricultural plots had a mean C:N ratio of 11.3 ± 1.5 in soil grain sizes &lt;2 mm. Average C:N ratios for all grain sizes, ranging from 3.5 to 18.8, are provided in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1005" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Table 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0155" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0185">Results summary</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0300" view="all">We seek to understand the factors influencing carbon stocks in riparian ecosystems which we evaluated through different treatment types, including various restoration approaches and Remnant forests. A key expectation was that carbon stocks increases with time, with highest values expected to be in the oldest plots: Remnant type plots. With the additional sequestration potential made possible by intensive planting efforts, we also expected Assisted type plots to result in more C than Process type plots. We evaluated competing hypotheses by comparing various potential influences of C values throughout the plots. It is important to note, however, the unbalanced nature of this study, limiting the potential for extensive statistical analysis. Key insights from each of the research questions are summarized here.</ce:para>
                     <ce:section id="s0160" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.5.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0190">What are the C stocks across the riparian corridor?</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0305" view="all">Our study revealed that various carbon stocks – biomass, large wood (LWD), and floodplain surface (litter and soil) – possess a distinct potential for carbon sequestration. Total C values range from 1.2 to 1099.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Within the various stocks, biomass held between 0.3 and 1010.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, LWD contained 53 to 569 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, 0.2 to 48.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> within litter, and 1.2 to 85.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in total soil. Individual stocks are broken down by treatment type in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1010" refid="f0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="f0030"/>. Total and average values for individual stocks are also available in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1015" refid="t0015">
                              <ce:bold>Tables 3</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cf1020" refid="t0020">
                              <ce:bold>Table 4</ce:bold>
                           </ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0165" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.5.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0195">Do C stocks vary across properties, treatment types, or time?</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0310" view="all">In quantifying the C stock within biomass, LWD, and floodplain surfaces across treatment types, we were ultimately comparing C values across time. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1025" refid="f0035">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="f0035"/> provides total C within each plot by time and classified by treatment type.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0315" view="all">Visually emphasized via log-transformation of the y-axis in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1030" refid="f0035">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref> and supported by a 0.87 Spearman correlation coefficient, C values have a logarithmic relationship with time supporting the ‘<ce:bold>non-linearity hypothesis’</ce:bold>. If we recall from <ce:cross-ref id="cf1035" refid="f0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>a, the oldest plots were distributed in the largest C values for the &lt;2 mm Soil fraction. Additionally, the highest biomass C values and litter C values (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1040" refid="f0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>b) were also found in the oldest plots, indicating C values increase with time.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0320" view="all">We conducted a one-way ANOVA evaluating the influence of treatment, treatment type, and time each as the independent variable with the resulting C values for each stock and total C as the dependent variable. Results indicate a notable influence from each independent variable on individual C stocks and cumulatively within total C values, with treatment type and time resulting in significant values. When we evaluated the influence of time combined with treatment type using a two-way ANOVA, the combination accounted for 41% of variance according to the Tukey's HSD post-hoc test (resulting tables for each of these ANOVAs are available in <ce:bold>Appendix C</ce:bold>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0170" view="all">
                        <ce:label>4.5.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st0200">Do specific restoration action types create desired trajectories or outcomes?</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0325" view="all">This study found a positive correlation between woody species richness and C stocks in biomass, suggesting that restoration strategies that focus on improving species richness could also enhance carbon sequestration. In addition, plots dominated by <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> that were not in remnant type plots had lower biomass than their equivalent in time with different dominant woody species composition. This correlation challenges the approach of planting a single climax species as a means to increase C. These results support the ‘<ce:italic>species composition hypothesis</ce:italic>’.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0330" view="all">Desired trajectories are, ultimately, dependent on the restoration practitioner and the target objectives. For example, some properties within the Assisted and Hybrid type plots had <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> stems or acorns planted as mitigation for the loss of individual mature <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> trees in regional infrastructure construction (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1045" refid="bb0570">Sweet, 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Other properties were chosen for Process type treatments which identified ‘restore riparian forest characteristics’ as their target and intentionally breached levees in the hope that reconnecting the natural flow regime to the disconnected floodplain would facilitate desired outcomes (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1050" refid="bb0255">Kleinschmidt, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1055" refid="bb0330">Marty and Davis, 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1060" refid="bb0585">The Nature Conservancy, 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0335" view="all">Because ‘desired trajectories’ or ‘outcomes’ is case dependent, we evaluate resulting C stock values within four treatment types (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1065" refid="bb0420">Napora et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). If the desired outcome is higher total C values, or higher biomass Process type plots created the most desired trajectories. If high soil C values in &lt;2 mm soil fraction or total, is the desired outcome, Assisted type plots created the best results. However, both Assisted and Process types resulted in lower C stock values than Remnant type plots, thus time will always be an essential component.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0175" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0205">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0340" view="all">This study addresses a key gap by quantifying the largest C stocks as identified by <ce:cross-ref id="cf1070" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref>, aboveground biomass, LWD, and floodplain surfaces (litter and soil) within four treatment types (23 different treatment actions provided in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1075" refid="t0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>) across a multi-decadal chronosequence in Mediterranean-montane riparian floodplains. C stock estimates within Mediterranean riparian zones are extremely limited (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1080" refid="t0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). Though many of the treatments investigated here did not fully articulate a long-term objective for their actions, local Remnant riparian forests provide excellent reference points. With treatments available through time, we are able to evaluate the influence variables may have on resulting C stock values. Without defined theoretical justification, the case for many treatments, we evaluated competing hypotheses by comparing various potential influences of C values throughout the plots. We discuss the theoretical hypotheses as they apply to our three research questions:</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="s0180" view="all">
                     <ce:label>5.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0210">What are the C stocks across the riparian corridor?</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0345" view="all">Our study revealed that various carbon stocks found in Mediterranean riparian corridors possess a distinct potential for carbon sequestration. Total C stocks across all plots range from 1.2 to 597.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, with average treatment type and stock values available in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1085" refid="t0015">
                           <ce:bold>Tables 3</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cf1090" refid="t0020">
                           <ce:bold>Table 4</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref>. Studies conducted in similar ecosystems or on similar woody species found comparable values to our results (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1095" refid="t0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:cross-ref id="cf1100" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> found total C stocks in plots 30 years post-restoration treatment to vary from 75.7 to 137.4 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> and from 95.1 to 175.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> after 100 years in Mediterranean riparian systems, though they did suspect soil C to be insufficiently accounted for in their study. Biomass, alone, ranged from 42.8 Mg C ha to 101.2 after 30 years (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1105" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Similarly, <ce:cross-ref id="cf1110" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al. (2019a)</ce:cross-ref> estimated that riparian forest biomass contains 145.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> on average and up to 487 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0350" view="all">Our resulting averages for biomass are 128.0 ± 161.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2020 and 96.1 ± 114.7 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in 2012 across all plots. Time since treatment varied widely and plots were not uniformly distributed across time. Because Process type includes many plots with recent treatment (ten years or less), comparing treatments with similar time values more accurately demonstrates the long-term accrual of C within stocks. To compare treatments, such as Assisted type plots, which have an average of 31 years since restoration treatment, against Process type, we identified average C values for plots ∼31 years post-treatment for Process treatment type plots. The resulting values were 172.0 ± 60.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Process compared to the average Assisted value of 108.5 ± 37.1 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> when reduced to only plots with ∼31 years since treatment. The difference between treatments is more discernable when values are constrained to comparable time ranges. Both values exceed biomass values reported by <ce:cross-ref id="cf1115" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> and align with upper biomass values found by <ce:cross-ref id="cf1120" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al. (2019a)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0355" view="all">The significant contribution of large individual Valley Oak (<ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic>) to overall biomass and within the highest C value plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1125" refid="f0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>) is important because of the prevalence of <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> in Assisted planting schemes. A single plot within our sampling with only two statistically outlying stems (152.1 and 166.3 cm DBH) resulted in a C value of &gt;1100 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. This plot was removed from statistical analysis because, unlike other statistical outliers, it was also markedly dissimilar from all other plots. However, this plot provides an ideal example of the potential long-term value of <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> in either Oak savanna or riparian forests for carbon sequestration. In this region, <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> is described with an average DBH of 50–70 cm with accounts of &gt;200 cm DBH available (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1130" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>). If allowed to recover, late-seral Oak savanna forests could provide the largest volume of sequestered C in their ecosystem (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1135" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1140" refid="bb0370">McCreary and Tecklin, 2005</ce:cross-ref>). However, <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> are slow-growing and show extremely limited success when actively propagated. Several Assisted and Hybrid type plots had <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> propagated but there was frequent sapling loss, or sometimes complete sampling die off, between 2012 and 13 and 2020–21. As a late-seral to climax stage species, biogeophysical processes seem essential to achieve the mass now present in these large individuals (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1145" refid="bb0195">Griffin, 1977</ce:cross-ref>). Process type may have more potential to create, capture, and store C in heterogeneous stocks by supporting these required biogeophysical processes, including <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> recruitment in older plots. Because there are limited anthropogenetic influences through restoration actions in Process type, results are primarily driven by environmental factors. Active channel flow connection allows for differential niches of sediment, nutrients, and moisture regimes that in turn support rapid growth and higher species richness. Varied floodplain inundation with frequency and magnitude specific to each location could be a key driver in the highly heterogeneous nature of biomass C values in Process type plots. These processes support the ‘<ce:bold>habitat heterogeneity hypothesis</ce:bold>’ through the development of differential niches and the <ce:bold>‘disturbance hypothesis’</ce:bold> by using a system-specific disturbance regime (i.e. flooding) to develop such niches.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0360" view="all">The resulting soil and litter C values from this study also align with available published findings. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1150" refid="bb0355">Matzek et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> estimated that riparian forest soil C measurements are 38.7 ± 5.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Remnant, 32 ± 1 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Process, and 25 ± 1.2 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Assisted. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1155" refid="bb0170">Gaman (2008)</ce:cross-ref> quantified values for valley oaks and found litter to account for 31 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, soil to have 28 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, and downed wood to account for 21 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Our findings for total C in soil exceed these values with an average of 36.9 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> across all plots. Litter measurements within these plots feel short of the litter values measured by <ce:cross-ref id="cf1160" refid="bb0170">Gaman (2008)</ce:cross-ref>, averaging 4.8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>. Other studies have added an additional 7.5 to 188 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in root biomass with 7.5 to 109 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> measured in temperate riparian areas (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1165" refid="bb0560">Sutfin et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). The Agriculture values seem comparatively lower than other treatment values, however <ce:cross-ref id="cf1170" refid="bb0405">Murty et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref> found soil C to be reduced by 40 % or more after 50 years, a shorter time frame than these lands have been agriculture.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0185" view="all">
                     <ce:label>5.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0215">Do C stocks vary across properties, treatment types, or time?</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0365" view="all">We hypothesized that aboveground carbon would be highest in Remnant and Assisted treatment type plots because of the time since treatment and planting intensity, respectively (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1175" refid="bb0345">Matzek et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1180" refid="bb0565">Sweeney et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>). Remnant plots had more than double the highest aboveground biomass and C values of any other treatment, partially confirming our expectation. This aligns with <ce:cross-ref id="cf1185" refid="bb0175">Giese et al. (2003)</ce:cross-ref> who found mature, undisturbed riparian forests to contain four times more C than younger neighbors. We found Process type plots, however, to produce greater aboveground biomass C values (96.3 ± 72.3) than Assisted plots (50.1 ± 33.0). With the prevalence of <ce:italic>Q. lobata</ce:italic> used for planting schemes and the average time since treatment of Assisted plots, more than a decade longer than the Process plot average, these results were unexpected. Interestingly, however, higher C values in litter, total soil, and &lt;2 mm soil fractions are found in Assisted type plots. As discussed in the Results section, the two-way ANOVA indicate both time and treatment type are influential for total C. However, total C, over time, is greater in Process than Assisted type plots accumulating to a maximum value of 285.0 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Process type plots and only 155.1 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in Assisted. A positive correlation between woody species richness and C stocks in biomass, the case in Process plots, suggests that restoration strategies that focus on improving species richness could also enhance carbon sequestration. Carbon values within Hybrid type plots were consistently the lowest in Total C, Biomass C, Litter C, and Soil C.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0370" view="all">Comparisons of LWD contributions to Total C cannot be directly conducted because similar surveys and data collection were not available for older properties. Investigations into historic aerial imagery, however, show no evidence of similarly extensive LWD or logjams around the narrower levee alterations and failures within other restoration sites. This assessment is supported by several previous studies within CRP (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1190" refid="bb0140">Florsheim and Mount, 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1195" refid="bb0400">Mount et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1200" refid="bb0425">Nichols and Viers, 2017</ce:cross-ref>) that do not discuss LWD in their discussions of erosion and deposition.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0190" view="all">
                     <ce:label>5.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st0220">Do specific restoration actions create desired trajectories or outcomes?</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0375" view="all">A desired trajectory or outcome within the context of floodplain restoration is typically defined by the restoration practitioner. However, variability within definitions is vast. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1205" refid="bb0140">Florsheim and Mount (2002)</ce:cross-ref> define ‘restoration’ within the context of ‘rehabilitation’ supporting the <ce:italic>trajectory toward</ce:italic> self-sustaining recovery rather than fully recovered to a pre-disturbed state. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1210" refid="bb0270">Kondolf (2011)</ce:cross-ref> points out that in the US, ‘restoration’ projects that are typically funded do not restore function, rather strategically plant riparian species or deploy other natural materials (e.g. boulders or logs) to arrest bank erosion and stabilize channel flows regardless of ecological recovery. Ultimately, <ce:cross-ref id="cf1215" refid="bb0245">Kaiser et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> find that though the emergence of ecosystem services as a concept has increased the discussion of potential metrics for ‘desired’ or ‘successful’ outcomes, there is little consistency when ecosystem services are assessed. However, carbon sequestration is increasingly identified as a primary justification for riparian floodplain restoration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1220" refid="bb0130">Dybala et al., 2019a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1225" refid="bb0360">Matzek et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1230" refid="bb0420">Napora et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1235" refid="bb0530">Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, C stock values as high or higher than reported values within comparable investigations is considered a desired outcome within this analysis. Thus, a positive correlation between species composition (higher species richness) and C stock would support the ‘<ce:italic>species composition hypothesis</ce:italic>’ that more species indicates higher functionality and ability to accumulate C within stocks more efficiently compared to monocultures of late-seral or climax species.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0380" view="all">Heavy debate within the literature complicates identifying the best riparian restoration methods (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1240" refid="bb0080">Castro et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1245" refid="bb0230">Holl, 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1250" refid="bb0245">Kaiser et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:cross-ref id="cf1255" refid="bb0135">Dybala et al. (2019b)</ce:cross-ref> argue that Assisted approaches jumpstart C accumulation and provide more immediate results, encouraging planting schemes. However, <ce:cross-ref id="cf1260" refid="bb0350">Matzek et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> found that increased biomass does not equate to increased soil C or a restored system, even when 20 years had passed since Assisted restoration with intensive planting. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1265" refid="bb0010">Albrecht et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> found Assisted treatment actions ineffective in C accumulation, biodiversity, or ecosystem functionality due to low survivability. When surveying planted plots, 24% of species planted were no longer present and 28% of species were almost completely absent three years after planting (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1270" refid="bb0010">Albrecht et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Similarly, within CRP some properties lost all acorns or saplings planted as part of Assisted restoration actions. As the major aboveground C stock, and the largest stock measured here, planting decisions have the potential to influence biomass C and other C stocks values throughout a floodplain riparian system, including litter and soil stocks.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0385" view="all">Litter presence has also been shown to have a positive relationship with soil C (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1275" refid="bb0660">Xu et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1280" refid="bb0670">Zhou et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Specific species compositions and their litter, however, can influence soil C differently. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1285" refid="bb0455">Pérez-Corona et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> found that while organic C and total N were positively correlated, planted forests showed lower C and N compared to their naturally recruited equivalent. These findings aligned with other investigations into soil C dynamics in planted forests that showed lower values that process- or succession-based restoration (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1290" refid="bb0300">Liao et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1295" refid="bb0350">Matzek et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1300" refid="bb0490">Roa-Fuentes et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). When considering the same time since treatment for plots, however, we found that average and maximum soil C values were greater in Assisted type plots than Process type, but average C:N values were similar (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1305" refid="t0020">
                           <ce:bold>Table 4</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref>). This may be due, in part, to variations in the soil microbiome and decomposition processes. As nitrogen mineralization occurs during microbial digestion, the ratio of carbon to nitrogen decreases (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1310" refid="bb0180">Gillespie et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1315" refid="bb0520">Shrestha et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). Essentially, as the carbon to nitrogen ratio is reduced, less carbon is available for microbial digestion and more available for absorption by plants (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1320" refid="bb0320">Magdoff, 1994</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1325" refid="bb0335">Matejovic, 1997</ce:cross-ref>). Because grain size dictates C availability for microbial digestion, the fractions of each grain size in <ce:cross-ref id="cf1330" refid="t0020">
                           <ce:bold>Table 4</ce:bold>
                        </ce:cross-ref> are relevant here. Within Process type plots, &lt;2 mm grain size is 60.5% of total soil, and 41.5% in ∼30 year old plots, while Assisted type plots have 32.9% of the total soil within the &lt;2 mm grain size. This means that of the total soil C in each treatment type, more Assisted soil C is not accessible for microbial digestion making it more volatile and Process type plots have more C that is more likely to be sequestered.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0390" view="all">The complex relationship between the C:N ratio and soil C and each of these variables with other stocks, such as litter C, is expected to be influenced by climate change. <ce:cross-ref id="cf1335" refid="bb0665">Zhou et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> found that climate and the C:N ratio of litter to be constraining factors on soil C accumulation. Similarly, <ce:cross-ref id="cf1340" refid="bb0205">Hao et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> identified aridity as a key driver in C and N dynamics with impacts on soil quality, nutrient availability, litter decomposition, and other biogeochemical processes while <ce:cross-ref id="cf1345" refid="bb0035">Barragán et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> provide evidence that trees planted during restoration efforts will have mixed results under climate change.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0395" view="all">A major challenge in riparian floodplain restoration, especially in evaluating past treatments, is the absence of desired outcomes or trajectories. If we consider the goal of a restoration treatment to generally restore floodplain functionality and biogeochemical processes that allow for C stock development, then we can argue that each plot contains some C stocks. Because C sequestration was not an articulated goal for these restoration treatments, we can only evaluate how much each treatment type now has stored, rather than how successful a given restoration type was at sequestering C. Our findings highlight the nuanced differences possible with different time allowances, treatment approaches, and management types, all possible by long term monitoring. More importantly, other restoration sites cannot contribute to improving restoration treatments if similar long-term monitoring is not implemented, especially as we face the impacts of climate change. Riparian corridors are identified as resilient to disturbance and climatic variability because of the system nuances that rely on disturbances to facilitate its emblematic habitat mosaic (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1350" refid="bb0410">Naiman and Décamps, 1997</ce:cross-ref>). As climate change impacts increasingly threaten species and ecosystems, riparian restoration will need to consider treatment choices that reach site specific objectives while also aligning with climate mitigation goals (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1355" refid="bb0495">Seavy et al., 2009a</ce:cross-ref>). Without riparian corridors that provide a vital refuge from heat and exposure, the detrimental impacts of arid climate extremes are expected to exacerbate climate-based ecosystem loss (<ce:cross-ref id="cf1360" refid="bb0065">Capon et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cf1365" refid="bb0495">Seavy et al., 2009a</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0195" view="all">
                  <ce:label>6</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st0225">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0400" view="all">This study quantifies and compares C stocks across a chronosequence of restoration approaches in Mediterranean-montane floodplain ecosystems, addressing a critical gap in carbon accounting for these vulnerable and understudied regions. By investigating aboveground biomass, large wood, and floodplain surface (soil and litter) C pools, we provide valuable insights into these ecosystems' carbon storage potential and dynamics under different restoration strategies.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0405" view="all">Our findings demonstrate that process-based restoration promotes more significant C stock accumulation in aboveground biomass and large wood than assisted restoration plantings over similar time scales. However, assisted restoration results in higher total soil and litter C, suggesting complex interactions between the restoration approach and carbon storage pathways. Species composition, successional trajectories, and time since restoration influence these outcomes. Notably, the results highlight that planting oak-dominated compositions does not necessarily accelerate C stock accumulation to the levels found in remnant forests.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0410" view="all">The Cstocks quantified in this study underscore the urgent and significant role of Mediterranean floodplain and riparian ecosystems as biodiversity hotspots and carbon sinks. These ecosystems are increasingly threatened by climate change, but their inherent resilience and potential to provide refuge for diverse species during extreme events make them crucial and immediate targets for conservation and restoration efforts. Our research emphasizes the pressing need for quantitative C accounting and strategic management of these C stocks as central components of restoration initiatives.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0415" view="all">Moreover, this study not only provides insights into the complexities and trade-offs involved in selecting restoration strategies for Mediterranean riparian ecosystems in the context of climate change mitigation, but also offers practical guidance. Process-based restoration may prioritize biomass C accumulation, while assisted restoration could be employed to strategically foster total soil C. These findings can directly inform more targeted, climate-conscious restoration policies and practices in Mediterranean regions and similar temperate floodplain ecosystems worldwide.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0420" view="all">Future studies should prioritize long-term monitoring and detailed C accounting across various restoration sites and techniques. Investigating the mechanisms underlying the observed C stock dynamics, such as species interactions, hydrological processes, and soil microbial communities, could provide deeper insights into the factors driving C sequestration in these ecosystems. Integrating carbon storage objectives with other ecosystem services and biodiversity conservation goals will also be essential for developing comprehensive, multi-benefit restoration strategies.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0425" view="all">In conclusion, this study advances our understanding of C stocks in Mediterranean-montane floodplain ecosystems and the impacts of different restoration approaches on C sequestration. The findings highlight the importance of these ecosystems as carbon sinks and biodiversity hotspots, underlining the need for their conservation and strategic restoration in the face of climate change. This research contributes to developing more effective and resilient management strategies for these critical ecosystems by providing a foundation for informed, climate-conscious restoration decision-making for both local ecosystem needs and global climate mitigation.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0200" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st0230">Funding</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0430" view="all">This work is supported by <ce:grant-sponsor id="gts0005" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Agriculture and Food Research Initiative Competitive</ce:grant-sponsor> Grant no. <ce:grant-number id="gtn0005" refid="gts0005">2021–69012-35916</ce:grant-number> from the <ce:grant-sponsor id="gts0010" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">USDA National Institute of Food and Agriculture AFRI SAS Secure Water Future</ce:grant-sponsor>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
